ough the end of the Cold War. The gay and lesbian left found its center in the San Francisco Bay Area, a place where sexual self-determination and revolutionary internationalism converged. Across the 1970s, its activists embraced socialist and women of color feminism and crafted queer opposition to militarism and the New Right. In the Reagan years, they challenged U.S. intervention in Central America, collaborated with their peers in Nicaragua, and mentored the first direct action against AIDS. Bringing together archival research, oral histories, and vibrant images, Emily K. Hobson rediscovers the radical queer past for a generation of activists today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aGay liberation movementzUnited States. 0aSexual minoritieszUnited States. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh  a1960s.  a1970s.  aactivism.  aactivist.  aaids.  aanti war.  abay area.  ablack feminism.  acold war.  agovernment.  aimperialism.  aleftist.  algbtq activism.  algbtq.  aoral history.  apeople of color.  apolitical.  aqueer activism.  aqueer activist.  aqueer radical.  aqueer.  aracism.  aradical politics.  areagan years.  arevolution.  arevolutionary.  asan francisco.  asexual liberation.  asocial movements.  asocial studies.  asocialist.  astonewall.  awar.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831106675470 cprintz978052027905640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780520965706?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520965706423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520965706/original  a978-3-11-066754-7  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY